Hi Thomas,

On 10/22/07, Thomas  SMETS &lt;smetsthomas@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;  My specific class relies on its parent to execute most of the hard work
&gt;
&gt;  public class DB1Validation extends DBValidation {
&gt;
&gt;  public String ds = &quot;jdbc/DB1&quot;;
&gt;
&gt;  public static final TestSuite suite()
&gt;       {
&gt;           TestSuite suite = new TestSuite(DB1Validation.class);
&gt;           String[] tables = new String[]
&gt;                   {&quot;ERRORS&quot;, &quot;ERROR_CODES&quot;, &quot;EVENTS&quot;, &quot;MASKS&quot; };
&gt;
&gt;  suite.addTest(validateAllTables(tables));
&gt;
&gt;  return suite;
&gt;       }
&gt;  }
&gt;
&gt;  If I don&#39;t create a suite-method, the code DB1Validation invokes the
&gt;  parent test (accessDBSuccessfull) successfully. If I do create a suite
&gt;  method as indicated, I get the following error :
&gt;  &lt;pre&gt;
&gt;  junit.framework.AssertionFailedError: No tests found in (snipped)
&gt;  .env.db.DB1Validation

What is happening is that JUnit 4&#39;s backwards compatibility kicks in
when it sees a suite() method in the test class. It then proceeds to
look for test methods defined with the JUnit 3.8-style signatures
rather than based on the JUnit 4 annotations.

